# Fableland — Wonder Items GDD

Design doc for the wonder-item layer: slots, acquisition, anatomy (passive / skill /
cooldown), features/tags, lifecycle patterns, and the item catalog.

Implementation target: `Scripts/Items/`. First landing: **v0.6.0**.

---

## 1. Overview

Wonder items are **equipment** that modify stats, grant activatable skills, or provide
passive effects. They are the primary horizontal-progression layer within a run — more
items mean more options, but only a few can be active at once.

### 1.1 Slots

| Container | Capacity | Effect |
|-----------|----------|--------|
| **Held slot** | 1 per protagonist (3 max with a full party) | Passive is active; skill is usable; cooldown ticks down at day-end resolution. |
| **Backpack** | Unlimited | Items are carried but **inert** — no passive, skill unavailable, cooldown does **not** tick. |

The player can swap items between backpack and held slots at any **shelter node**
(Blessed or Mundane; see `NODES.gdd` §5.1). Held slots are per-protagonist.

**Benching rule:** when a protagonist is benched, their held item **auto-returns to
the backpack**. Team build and item assignment can only be changed at a shelter node,
so the player cannot bench a protagonist mid-combat or mid-exploration to shuffle items.

> The party cap and held-slot cap can be modified by certain items or mechanisms
> (e.g., "A Weird Mushroom" outcome f).

### 1.2 Acquisition

| Source | Likelihood |
|--------|-----------|
| Combat node — mission reward | Guaranteed for first-successful completion of certain nodes |
| Foe drop | Very low chance on kill (see `FOES.gdd` §7 loot hooks; **TODO:** add wonder-item row to the FOES loot table) |
| Question-mark node — story event | Variable, depending on the event |
| VOID trader | Barter with wonder cores or other items (see `NODES.gdd` §5.3) |
| Jousting | The wanderer's held item transfers on victory |
| Plantation harvest | Harvesting a planted item yields its fruit |
| Item conversion | Some items transform into others after use |
| **TODO** | Foes may rarely **hold** a wonder item and use it in combat; killing them drops it |

---

## 2. Item anatomy

Every wonder item has up to four components:

| Component | Required? | Description |
|-----------|-----------|-------------|
| **Passive** | Optional | Always-on effect while the item is **held** (or always, if it has the `Possession` tag). |
| **Skill** | Optional | An activatable ability. May be combat-only, map-only, or either. |
| **Cooldown** | Only if the item has a Skill | How long before the skill can be used again. Two types: day-based and second-based (§3). |
| **Features / Tags** | Optional | Special behaviours: perishable, convertible, plantable, possession, eternal (§4). |

An item with no passive, no skill, and no features is a **dormant** item (e.g., a
consumed remnant waiting to be planted). Dormant items still occupy their slot.

---

## 3. Cooldown system

There are **two cooldown axes**, independent of each other:

### 3.1 Day-based cooldown (world-map / exploration skills)

Measured in **days**. At **day-end resolution** (when the player clicks "Finish the Day";
see `NODES.gdd` §7), every **held** item's cooldown decrements by 1. Items in the
backpack do **not** tick down.

| CD | Behaviour |
|----|-----------|
| 0 (no CD) | Passive only; no skill. |
| 1 day | Can be used once per day. Resets at day-end resolution. |
| 2 days | Use → 2 full day-end resolutions must pass → usable again on day 3. |
| Single-use | Use once → skill is consumed. The item may convert or become dormant. |

Day-based skills can be used **either** during combat **or** on the world map,
depending on the item's design. Some items specify "combat only" or "map only."

### 3.2 Second-based cooldown (combat skills)

Measured in **real-time seconds** during combat. Functions identically to protagonist
ability cooldowns — ticks down with the arena clock, unaffected by the day cycle.

| Example CD | Item |
|------------|------|
| 15 s | The Forgotten Kashaya (knockback) |
| 30 s | FanChen's Heart (self-Freeze), Yukai's Rope (grapple) |

An item may have **both** a day-based CD and a second-based CD if it has two skills
(not currently spec'd, but the architecture supports it).

---

## 4. Feature / tag catalog

Tags modify how the item behaves in the world. An item can carry **multiple** tags.

### 4.1 `Perishable`

If not used within N days, the item is destroyed (or converts to a rotten/expired
form). The countdown ticks at **day-end resolution regardless of whether the
item is held or in the backpack**. A perishable item in the backpack will still rot.

| Perish timer | Consequence on expiry |
|-------------|----------------------|
| N days | Item is removed from inventory; may be replaced by a "rotten" variant. |

*Example: A Weird Mushroom — 2 days → A Rotten Mushroom.*

### 4.2 `Convertible`

After the item's skill is used (or a condition is met), the item is **replaced** by
a different item in the same slot. The new item inherits the slot position (held or
backpack). Convertible items cannot also be `Eternal` — the two tags are mutually
exclusive (§4.5).

*Examples:*
- Pome's Bravery → Pome's Seed (after skill use)
- Pixolotl's Feather → Pixolotl's Wish (after skill use)
- A Weird Mushroom → A Rotten Mushroom (perish expiry)

### 4.3 `Plantable`

The item can be **planted** in a plantation slot at a shelter node (see `NODES.gdd`
§5.2 and the separate **Plantation GDD**). Plantable items have:

| Attribute | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| **Harvest time** | Days until the plant bears fruit. |
| **Fruit** | A list of wonder items produced at harvest (quantity and type). |
| **Inheritance** | Optional — the fruit's stats may inherit a range (e.g., 60%–140%) of the parent item's attributes, rolled at harvest time. |

*Examples:*
- Pome's Seed — 4 days, harvests 1–3× Pome's Bravery with random stats
- Pixolotl's Wish — 7 days, harvests 2× Pixolotl's Feather
- A Rotten Mushroom — 4 days, generates 4× Weird Mushrooms with inherited HP range + random consequence

### 4.4 `Possession`

The item's **passive is always active**, even when the item is in the backpack (not
held). The skill still requires the item to be held.

*Example: THE VOID — its phantom-spawning passive works from the backpack.*

The `Possession` tag can also be **added** to another item via certain meta-items
(e.g., The Blessing of Shieldon's skill). However, `Eternal` items resist this —
they cannot be enchanted (§4.5).

### 4.5 `Eternal`

The item **cannot** be:
- Traded (VOID trader rejects it)
- Enchanted / upgraded (resists modification by meta-items such as Blessing of Shieldon)
- Deserted / dropped / voluntarily removed from inventory
- **Converted** into another item (mutually exclusive with the `Convertible` tag)

This is typically a **negative** tag attached to cursed or burdensome items.
`Eternal` + `Possession` together mean the item is a permanent, inescapable modifier
for the entire run.

*Example: THE VOID — Eternal + Possession; the phantoms follow you forever.*

---

## 5. Item lifecycle patterns

Items fall into several lifecycle archetypes:

### 5.1 Static
Held → provides passive ± skill on cooldown → stays the same item forever.
*Examples: FanChen's Heart, Yukai's Rope, The Forgotten Kashaya, DD.*

### 5.2 Single-use → convert
Held → skill used → converts to a successor item. The successor may be dormant,
plantable, or a different static item.
*Examples: Pome's Bravery → Pome's Seed, Pixolotl's Feather → Pixolotl's Wish,
The Blessing of Shieldon (consumed on use).*

### 5.3 Perishable → convert
Held or in backpack → timer expires → converts to rotten/dormant form.
*Example: A Weird Mushroom → A Rotten Mushroom.*

### 5.4 Plantable → harvest
Planted at shelter → grows over N days → harvested for fruit items. The planted
item is consumed (removed from inventory) when planted.
*Examples: Pome's Seed, Pixolotl's Wish, A Rotten Mushroom.*

### 5.5 Conditional trigger
Held → condition met (e.g., boss killed) → effect fires → item may be consumed.
*Example: QiongFeng Emperor of LOONG's Claw — boss kill triggers loot sweep +
world crack + teleport, then claw faints.*

---

## 6. Classification

### 6.1 By usage domain

| Domain | Description | Examples |
|--------|-------------|----------|
| **Combat** | Passive + skill both function inside the arena. Cooldown is second-based. | FanChen's Heart, Yukai's Rope, The Forgotten Kashaya, THE VOID (skill is combat-only) |
| **Exploration** | Passive and/or skill affect the overworld map. Cooldown is day-based. | QiongFeng Emperor's Claw |
| **Hybrid** | Combat passive + world-map skill, or vice versa. May have both CD types. | DD (combat passive + day-based skill), Pome's Bravery (combat passive + single-use skill → plantable), Pixolotl's Feather (combat passive + day-rewind skill), A Weird Mushroom (single-use combat buff + next-day world effect) |

### 6.2 By lifecycle archetype

See §5 — Static, Single-use→convert, Perishable→convert, Plantable→harvest, Conditional trigger.

### 6.3 By tag matrix

| Item | Perishable | Convertible | Plantable | Possession | Eternal |
|------|-----------|-------------|-----------|------------|---------|
| Blessing of Shieldon | — | — | — | — (grants it) | — |
| THE VOID | — | — | — | ✓ | ✓ |
| DD | — | — | — | — | — |
| Pome's Bravery | — | ✓ (→Seed) | — | — | — |
| Pome's Seed | — | — | ✓ (4d) | — | — |
| FanChen's Heart | — | — | — | — | — |
| Yukai's Rope | — | — | — | — | — |
| Pixolotl's Feather | — | ✓ (→Wish) | — | — | — |
| Pixolotl's Wish | — | — | ✓ (7d) | — | — |
| Forgotten Kashaya | — | — | — | — | — |
| QiongFeng Emperor's Claw | — | ✓ (on trigger) | — | — | — |
| A Weird Mushroom | ✓ (2d) | ✓ (→Rotten) | — | — | — |
| A Rotten Mushroom | — | — | ✓ (4d) | — | — |

> **Rule:** `Eternal` and `Convertible` are mutually exclusive. No item in the catalog
> carries both, and no future item should.

